    oneLiner: "Bodily pleasures are shared with animals and pertain to the body rather than the soul's highest operation, so they cannot constitute true human happiness.",
    body: "In S.T. I-II, q.2, a.6, Aquinas argues that happiness does not consist in bodily pleasure. Bodily pleasures arise from the satisfaction of sensory appetites — food, drink, sexual activity — and are common to humans and animals. But human happiness must correspond to what is highest and most distinctive in human nature: the intellect. Furthermore, bodily pleasure is a consequence of obtaining some good, not the good itself; it accompanies the attainment of what the appetite desires. The ultimate end must be the good itself, not the pleasure that follows from it. Finally, bodily pleasures are fleeting, partial, and often followed by pain or satiety — they cannot provide the complete, lasting fulfillment that true happiness requires.",
    example: "After a magnificent feast, a person feels full and satisfied — for a time. But within hours, hunger returns. The pleasure was real but temporary, tied to bodily processes that cycle endlessly. The soul's deepest longing is for something that satisfies permanently.",
