    tags: ["Aquinas", "Summa Theologica", "Beatific Vision", "Happiness", "God", "Eschatology"],
    oneLiner: "Perfect happiness consists in the intellectual vision of God's essence, since only the infinite good can completely and permanently satisfy the human will.",
    body: "In S.T. I-II, q.3, a.8, Aquinas reaches the culmination of his analysis of happiness: perfect beatitude consists in seeing God's essence (the beatific vision). His reasoning proceeds from what has been established: happiness must consist in the operation of the highest human power (intellect) directed toward the highest object (God). Since every created good is finite and particular, no created good can fully satisfy the will, which is naturally oriented toward the universal good. Only God, who is infinite goodness itself, can completely fill the will's capacity. This vision is not achieved by natural powers alone but requires the supernatural 'light of glory' (lumen gloriae) that elevates the intellect beyond its natural capacity. Perfect happiness is therefore eschatological — it awaits us in heaven.",
    example: "No matter how many beautiful sunsets, loving relationships, or intellectual achievements a person accumulates, there remains a restless longing for something more. Augustine captured this: 'You have made us for yourself, O Lord, and our heart is restless until it rests in you.' Aquinas demonstrates philosophically why this must be so.",
    whyItMatters: "This is one of the most important conclusions in the Summa. It orients the entire moral life toward an eternal destiny and shows that the deepest human desires point beyond this world. Every legitimate earthly good is a partial reflection of the infinite good we are made to enjoy forever in God's presence.",
