    category: "morality",
    tags: ["Aquinas", "Summa Theologica", "Happiness", "Beatitude", "Perseverance"],
    oneLiner: "Perfect happiness (beatitude) in heaven cannot be lost, while imperfect happiness in this life can always be lost through misfortune or sin.",
    body: "In S.T. I-II, q.5, a.4, Aquinas distinguishes between perfect and imperfect happiness regarding their permanence. Imperfect happiness, which is attainable in this life through virtue, contemplation, and friendship, can be lost — through illness, moral failure, the loss of loved ones, or other misfortunes. This is because earthly goods are inherently mutable and insecure. Perfect happiness (beatitude in heaven), however, cannot be lost. In the beatific vision, the will is so completely fulfilled by the infinite good that there is no possibility of turning away. The intellect sees God's essence with absolute clarity, and the will adheres to God with total love. There is no ignorance or weakness that could cause a falling away. This permanence is essential to perfect happiness: a happiness that could be lost would be shadowed by fear and therefore imperfect.",
    example: "A person in a wonderful marriage is happy but knows that death, illness, or betrayal could end this happiness. This shadow of insecurity proves it is imperfect happiness. In heaven, by contrast, the blessed know with certainty that their joy will never end — and this certainty is part of what makes it perfect.",
    whyItMatters: "This teaching gives Christians both realism and hope: realism about the fragility of earthly happiness, and unshakeable hope in the permanence of heavenly beatitude. It motivates perseverance in the spiritual life, knowing that the goal is a joy that can never be taken away.",
