    term: "Circumstances of Human Acts",
    category: "morality",
    tags: ["Aquinas", "Summa Theologica", "Circumstances", "Moral Theology", "Ethics"],
    oneLiner: "The morality of human actions is affected by their circumstances: who, what, where, by what means, why, how, and when.",
    body: "In S.T. I-II, q.7, Aquinas examines how circumstances modify the moral character of human acts. Drawing on Aristotle and Cicero, he identifies the key circumstances as: who acts (quis), what is done (quid), where (ubi), by what means or instruments (quibus auxiliis), why or for what motive (cur), how the act is performed (quomodo), and when (quando). While the moral species of an act is determined primarily by its object (what is done) and its end (why), circumstances can increase or diminish the goodness or evil of an act, and in some cases can even change its moral species. For example, stealing from a church adds the circumstance of sacrilege, changing the act from mere theft to a sin against both justice and religion. The 'why' (cur) is the most important circumstance, as it specifies the end intended by the agent.",
    example: "Giving money to a beggar (what) in public (where) to be seen by others (why) changes the moral quality of the act. The external action is the same as giving privately out of genuine charity, but the circumstance of vainglorious motive fundamentally alters its moral character.",
    whyItMatters: "This framework is essential for the examination of conscience and the practice of confession. It teaches Catholics to evaluate not just what they did but all the surrounding factors that shaped the moral meaning of their actions. It prevents both legalism (judging only the external act) and laxism (ignoring relevant factors).",
