    term: "Enjoyment (Fruitio) as Act of Will",
    category: "morality",
    tags: ["Aquinas", "Summa Theologica", "Enjoyment", "Fruitio", "Will", "Moral Psychology"],
    oneLiner: "Enjoyment or fruitio is the will's resting in the good finally attained; properly and perfectly, it belongs only to the last end.",
    body: "In S.T. I-II, q.11, Aquinas distinguishes between 'use' (uti) and 'enjoyment' (frui). To use something is to employ it as a means toward an end; to enjoy something is to rest in it with delight as an end. Properly speaking, enjoyment belongs only to the last end — the good in which the will finds complete rest and satisfaction (a.1). We may loosely speak of enjoying intermediate goods, but this is fruitio only in an improper sense, since the will does not find ultimate rest in them. Fruitio is therefore the consummation of the will's movement: the will first intends the end, then chooses means to it, and finally rests in the end when attained. Perfect fruitio is the beatific vision, where the will rests in God as the infinite good. In this life, our enjoyment is always imperfect because we have not yet fully attained our last end.",
    example: "A pilgrim walking to a shrine may enjoy the scenery along the way, but this enjoyment is imperfect — she does not stop and settle down beside a beautiful meadow. Her true enjoyment comes when she arrives at the shrine, the goal of her journey. Similarly, earthly joys are 'scenery along the way' to the soul's true destination in God.",
    whyItMatters: "This concept helps Catholics maintain proper ordering in their loves. Created goods are to be used (with gratitude) as means toward God, not clung to as ultimate ends. Disordered 'enjoyment' of creatures — treating them as the final resting place of the heart — is the root of idolatry and sin.",
