    category: "morality",
    tags: ["Aquinas", "Summa Theologica", "Intention", "Moral Theology", "Ethics"],
    oneLiner: "Intention is the act of the will directed toward the end as achieved through means; it shapes the morality of the whole act.",
    body: "In S.T. I-II, q.12, Aquinas analyzes intention (intentio) as a distinct act of the will. Intention differs from simple willing: simple willing bears on the end in itself, while intention bears on the end as to-be-attained-through-means (a.1). Intention thus includes within itself a reference to the means, even though it formally regards the end. One can intend the end without yet having determined the specific means (a.4), and one can have multiple intentions simultaneously — a soldier may fight both for victory and for pay (a.3). Crucially, intention shapes the moral character of the entire action. An externally good act done with a bad intention (like giving alms to be praised) is morally vitiated, while a good intention cannot make an intrinsically evil act good (a.1 ad 3). The end intended by the agent is one of the primary sources of morality alongside the object of the act and the circumstances.",
    example: "Two doctors perform identical surgeries. One intends to heal the patient; the other intends to practice a technique for a lucrative specialty. The external act is the same, but the intention changes the moral meaning: one acts from genuine care, the other from self-interest. Intention pervades and colors the entire act.",
    whyItMatters: "Intention is central to Catholic moral reasoning and the sacrament of confession. It explains why 'the end does not justify the means' — a good intention cannot redeem an intrinsically evil act — while also showing that a bad intention can corrupt an otherwise good deed. Moral integrity requires both right action and right intention.",
